"Prasad B.R., Senapati S.","Explaining the differential solubility of flue gas components in ionic liquids from first-principle calculations",2009,"Journal of Physical Chemistry B","113","14",,"4739","4743",,,10.1021/jp805249h,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-65249152019&partnerID=40&md5=3f42f0f772399e4db3dd021fc53bd51e","Department of Biotechnology, Indian Institute of Technology Madras, Chennai 600036, India","Prasad, B.R., Department of Biotechnology, Indian Institute of Technology Madras, Chennai 600036, India; Senapati, S., Department of Biotechnology, Indian Institute of Technology Madras, Chennai 600036, India","Flue gas is greatly responsible for acid rain formation and global warming. New generation ionic liquids (ILs) have potential in controlling the flue gas emissions, as they acquire high absorptivity for the component gases SO 2, CO2, etc. The association of the IL-gas interactions to the absorptivity of gas molecules in ILs is, however, poorly understood. In this paper, we present a molecular level description of the interactions of ILs with SO2, CO2, and N2 and show its implications to the differential gas solubility. Our results indicate that the IL anion-gas interactions play a key role in deciding the gas solubility in ILs, particularly for polar gases such as SO2. On the other hand, regular solution assumption applies to N2 solubility. In accordance with the previous theoretical and experimental findings, our results also imply that the IL anions dominate the interactions with gas molecules while the cations play a secondary role and the underlying fluid structures of the ILs remain unperturbed by the addition of gas molecules. © 2009 American Chemical Society.",,"Acid rain; Association reactions; Flue gases; Flues; Global warming; Ionic liquids; Ionization of liquids; Leakage (fluid); Molecules; Negative ions; Solubility; Ternary systems; Absorptivity; First-principle calculations; Flue gas; Flue gas components; Flue-gas emissions; Fluid structures; Gas interactions; Gas molecules; Gas solubilities; Molecular levels; Regular solutions; Gas emissions",,,,,,"Gorman, J., (2001) Sci. News, 160, pp. 156-158; Welton, T., (1999) Chem. Rev, 99, pp. 2071-2084; Zhao, H., Xia, S., Ma, P., (2005) J. Chem. Technol. Biotechnol, 80, pp. 1089-1096; Anderson, J.L., Dixon, J.K., Brennecke, J.F., (2007) Acc. Chem. Res, 40, pp. 1208-1216; Keskin, S., Kayrak-Talay, D., Akman, U., Hortacsu, O., (2007) J. Supercrit. Fluids, 43, pp. 150-180; Rao, A.B., Rubin, E.S., (2002) Environ. Sci. Technol, 36, pp. 4467-4475; Anthony, J.L., Maginn, E.J., Brennecke, J.F., (2002) J. Phys. Chem. B, 106, pp. 7315-7320; Muldoon, M. J.; Aki, S. N; V, K.; Anderson, J. L.; Dixon, J. K.; Brennecke, J. F. J. Phys. Chem. B 2007, 111, 9001-9009Kumelan, J., Kamps, A.P.S., Tuma, D., Maurer, G., (2006) J. Chem. Eng. Data, 51, pp. 11-14; Anderson, J.L., Dixon, J.K., Maginn, E.J., Brennecke, J.F., (2006) J. Phys. Chem. B, 110, pp. 15059-15062; Parson, E.A., Keith, D.W., (1998) Science, 282, pp. 1053-1054; Huang, J., Riisager, A., Wasserscheid, P., Fehrmann, R., (2006) Chem. Commun, 38, pp. 4027-4029; Blanchard, L.A., Gu, Z., Brennecke, J.F., (2001) J. Phys. Chem. B, 105, pp. 2437-2444; Anthony, J.L., Maginn, E.J., Brennecke, J.F., (2001) J. Phys. Chem. B, 105, pp. 10942-10949; Anthony, J.L., Anderson, J.L., Maginn, E.J., Brennecke, J.F., (2005) J. Phys. Chem. B, 109, pp. 6366-6374; Cadena, C., Anthony, J.L., Shah, J.K., Morrow, T.I., Brennecke, J.F., Maginn, E.J., (2004) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 126, pp. 5300-5308; Kazarian, S.G., Briscoe, B.J., Welton, T., (2000) Chem. Commun, 20, pp. 2047-2048; Cammarata, L., Kazarian, S.G., Salter, P.A., Welton, T., (2001) Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys, 3, pp. 5192-5200; Camper, D., Scovazzo, P., Koval, C., Noble, R., (2004) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res, 43, pp. 3049-3054; Kilaru, P.K., Scovazzo, P., (2008) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res, 47, pp. 910-919; Frisch, M.J., (2004) Gaussian 03, revision, (C.02). , Gaussian, Inc, Wallingford, C